WEBVTT

00:01.335 --> 00:05.005
OLIVER: Don't all true crime podcasters
wish they were on the case from the start?

00:05.005 --> 00:06.465
‐ Found someone dead.
CHARLES: What?

00:06.465 --> 00:09.134
LESTER: They offed themselves.
OLIVER: It's that guy from the elevator!

00:09.134 --> 00:11.220
‐ Tim Kono. With a K.

00:11.220 --> 00:13.180
CHARLES: What kinda guy
kills himself an hour after being

00:13.180 --> 00:15.516
desperate to get his hands on this?

00:15.516 --> 00:18.602
Now, the only thing that matters
is that there's a killer on the loose,

00:18.602 --> 00:19.978
and he could be living in our building.

00:20.437 --> 00:22.856
My father was a Charles. I'm a junior.

00:22.856 --> 00:24.983
‐ Are you?
‐ I'm Brazzos. [laughs]

00:24.983 --> 00:27.986
MABEL: Me and my Hardy Boys,
we would get into solving mysteries

00:27.986 --> 00:30.572
around the complex.
CHARLES: And your Hardy Boys,

00:30.572 --> 00:32.950
where are they now?

00:32.950 --> 00:34.451
♪

00:35.077 --> 00:37.579
[keys jingling]
[police radio chatter]

00:37.579 --> 00:41.166
♪ cop show theme playing ♪

00:41.166 --> 00:42.751
[metal door banging]

00:44.253 --> 00:47.130
‐ Looks like you arrested
the wrong guy, Detective.

00:47.756 --> 00:50.425
‐ Spare me the innocent act, Zeus.

00:50.425 --> 00:52.135
I got you dead‐to‐rights.

00:52.135 --> 00:55.180
‐ And I got 20 eyewitnesses who say

00:55.180 --> 00:57.975
I was at my niece's baptism last night.

00:58.809 --> 01:00.811
[emotionally]
It was a beautiful service.

01:02.354 --> 01:04.815
Only wish my mother was alive to see it.

01:04.815 --> 01:08.193
‐ Your lies might fool some people,
Zeus, but not me.

01:09.278 --> 01:11.697
I'm not some dumb cop you see on TV.

01:11.697 --> 01:13.532
I'm not Kojak.

01:13.532 --> 01:15.033
I'm not Tubbs.

01:16.201 --> 01:18.036
I'm Brazzos.

01:22.249 --> 01:25.961
[on computer]: This sends the
investigation into a whole new direction.

01:26.545 --> 01:29.214
By the way, I'm not calling
you Zeus anymore.

01:29.214 --> 01:32.217
That's your street name.

01:32.217 --> 01:35.846
I don't call anyone by their street name.
I call you by your real name...

01:35.846 --> 01:38.724
♪

01:38.724 --> 01:40.559
Mario Furstenberg.

01:41.435 --> 01:43.729
Oh, you think you're so special
because you had a rough dad.

01:44.605 --> 01:47.608
Let me tell you a little bit about my dad.

01:48.942 --> 01:51.361
It was the most constant refrain

01:51.361 --> 01:53.697
of my childhood. How much I was like him.

01:54.948 --> 01:56.658
"You're the spitting
image of your father."

01:56.658 --> 01:58.160
And I was.

01:58.785 --> 02:01.830
We were both right‐handed,
but we used scissors with our left hand.

02:01.830 --> 02:04.082
We could both pick up any instrument,

02:04.082 --> 02:05.959
just play it by ear.

02:08.545 --> 02:10.547
But ask us to do basic algebra?

02:10.547 --> 02:11.757
Forget about it.

02:13.467 --> 02:16.887
But you know,
people meant it as a compliment

02:17.638 --> 02:19.932
when they said I was like my father.

02:20.432 --> 02:22.851
But he was awful to my mother.

02:22.851 --> 02:25.562
He liked to make her feel small.
‐ The fuck?

02:26.438 --> 02:28.315
‐ Make her feel silly.

02:28.315 --> 02:29.733
Make her unsu‐‐
[click, stops video]

02:29.733 --> 02:32.736
♪ lively theme song playing ♪

02:37.407 --> 02:40.410
♪ vocalizing ♪

03:22.452 --> 03:25.455
♪

03:25.455 --> 03:27.749
CHARLES:
Every person is a mystery,

03:27.749 --> 03:29.710
but to care about a murder mystery,

03:29.710 --> 03:32.212
you need to care about the person
who was murdered.

03:32.212 --> 03:34.381
Who is Tim Kono?
[elevator dings]

03:34.381 --> 03:38.177
We know he lived on the ninth floor
of the Arconia in New York City.

03:38.177 --> 03:40.929
We know he had a mailbox.

03:40.929 --> 03:43.473
We know he got manicures,
or perhaps he just had

03:43.473 --> 03:45.517
naturally pleasing nail beds.

03:45.517 --> 03:48.353
This is terrible.
‐ Oh, I know. I literally feel myself

03:48.353 --> 03:50.022
aging when I listen to you.

03:50.022 --> 03:52.232
‐ It's your writing! I mean,
you don't know anything about the guy,

03:52.232 --> 03:53.483
so you're just saying the obvious.

03:53.483 --> 03:55.319
[gasps] It's so hot in here.

03:55.319 --> 03:57.112
"He was some sort of mixed Asian,

03:57.112 --> 03:59.573
"Japanese, Korean, or Chinese,

03:59.573 --> 04:01.950
maybe Indonesian?"
‐ Look, I am trying to target

04:01.950 --> 04:03.535
an entire continent here.

04:03.535 --> 04:05.579
That's four billion potential listeners.

04:05.579 --> 04:07.164
Ah, you're welcome.
‐ So hot in here.

04:07.164 --> 04:08.916
Do we have to do this in a closet?

04:08.916 --> 04:10.709
‐ [laughs] Well, now
you sound like Patti LuPone.

04:10.709 --> 04:12.669
No, no. The acoustics are better.

04:12.669 --> 04:14.171
And trust me, you need acoustics.

04:14.171 --> 04:17.174
[muffled]: Give me one more read. Come on.
And have lots of fun with it.

04:17.758 --> 04:19.801
CHARLES:
I'm about to pass out!

04:19.801 --> 04:21.845
Oh! How did you get here?

04:21.845 --> 04:23.639
‐ It was open.
‐ I don't lock my door.

04:23.639 --> 04:25.349
Never have.
‐ That's insane.

04:25.349 --> 04:26.642
‐ Neighborly.
MABEL: I mean, a murderer

04:26.642 --> 04:28.101
probably lives in the building,

04:28.101 --> 04:30.229
but I guess old white guys
are only afraid of

04:30.229 --> 04:32.105
colon cancer and societal change.

04:32.105 --> 04:33.106
Sad.

04:34.066 --> 04:36.235
‐ A murderer doesn't probably
live in the building.

04:36.235 --> 04:38.362
A murderer definitely
lives in the building!

04:38.362 --> 04:40.280
Lester checked all the security footage,

04:40.280 --> 04:42.783
and no one unknown to him came in or out

04:42.783 --> 04:44.159
during the hours around Tim's murder.

04:44.159 --> 04:46.161
‐ Isn't that great? For the podcast?
‐ So,

04:46.161 --> 04:47.287
Mabel, tell us.

04:47.704 --> 04:51.083
Did you learn anything from
the online world of Tim Kono?

04:51.792 --> 04:54.795
‐ He didn't post much in his online world.

04:54.795 --> 04:57.548
He seems to have had
a really sad, quiet life.

04:57.548 --> 04:59.049
‐ You checked all the websites?

04:59.675 --> 05:01.468
‐ Yep. All the websites.

05:01.468 --> 05:03.428
‐ Well, we've exhausted the internet.

05:03.428 --> 05:04.888
Oh! Before I forget,

05:04.888 --> 05:06.849
we should keep all our
evidence in one place,

05:06.849 --> 05:08.851
so I should probably hang
onto that engagement ring.

05:08.851 --> 05:10.269
‐ Why do you get to hang onto it?

05:11.186 --> 05:13.438
Don't you trust me, Brazzos?

05:13.438 --> 05:15.732
‐ It's our biggest clue.
We lose that, we've got nothing.

05:16.233 --> 05:18.610
‐ It's at my apartment.
I'll give it to you later.

05:18.610 --> 05:21.071
‐ Okay, guys, I‐I need you two to hear me.

05:21.822 --> 05:24.199
Our podcast is never going to pop

05:24.199 --> 05:27.369
until we know who is Tim Kono.

05:27.369 --> 05:28.787
‐ Who was Tim Kono.

05:29.454 --> 05:32.499
‐ Yeah, well, I've already named
the episode Who Is Tim Kono,

05:32.499 --> 05:34.293
so it's...
‐ Wait a minute!

05:34.293 --> 05:35.919
When did we finish episode one?
OLIVER: Dude,

05:35.919 --> 05:38.755
it's called a work in progress!

05:38.755 --> 05:40.674
Look, every great episode two

05:40.674 --> 05:42.509
always makes you care
deeply for the victim.

05:42.509 --> 05:44.678
CHARLES:
Ah, that's true. I've fallen in love

05:44.678 --> 05:46.847
with so many dead people.
‐ You either make them sympathetic

05:46.847 --> 05:49.141
or sexy or interesting, none of which

05:49.141 --> 05:50.893
I feel for Tim Kono, so.
‐ Look,

05:50.893 --> 05:53.687
someone in this building
had to have known him.

05:53.687 --> 05:55.063
We find that one person,

05:55.063 --> 05:56.940
and all this cracks open.
OLIVER: Mm‐hmm.

05:56.940 --> 05:58.358
[elevator dings]
TIM: Back off, Mabel.

05:58.859 --> 06:00.444
You can't disappear for 10 years,

06:00.444 --> 06:04.156
and then show up and start dragging up
a bunch of shit from when we were kids.

06:04.156 --> 06:05.657
‐ Oscar's getting out, Tim.

06:05.657 --> 06:08.577
You can make things right.
You know what happened that night.

06:08.577 --> 06:09.745
You didn't even say anything.

06:09.745 --> 06:11.747
‐ Look, if this is all
you came back for...

06:12.706 --> 06:14.333
I don't want to think about back then.

06:15.167 --> 06:16.668
I'm a different person now.

06:17.336 --> 06:19.838
‐ Jesus. We are different.

06:20.506 --> 06:22.466
And I don't need people
like you in my life.

06:22.466 --> 06:24.468
‐ Fine. Good. So...

06:25.177 --> 06:27.221
if you see me 'round the building,
act like you don't know me

06:27.221 --> 06:30.140
because you don't.
‐ Happily. Fuck you.

06:33.268 --> 06:35.270
What if Tim was a dick?

06:35.270 --> 06:37.523
‐ Hm. That's a definite angle.

06:38.273 --> 06:41.527
I mean, I wouldn't want him to be dickier
than Steve Carell in The Office.

06:41.527 --> 06:44.238
I‐I'd still care if Steve Carell
in The Office got murdered.

06:44.863 --> 06:45.906
Or would I?

06:46.406 --> 06:48.033
Thinking, thinking, visualizing.

06:48.033 --> 06:49.910
This is tough.
‐ We need to find someone who knew him.

06:49.910 --> 06:52.079
‐ [sighs] Here's an idea.

06:52.079 --> 06:55.415
It's a long shot, but they're
holding a memorial for Tim Kono

06:55.415 --> 06:57.918
in the lobby in 10 minutes.

06:58.377 --> 07:00.212
Maybe we learn something there.

07:00.212 --> 07:03.215
♪

07:04.925 --> 07:06.218
‐ God, she's good.

07:07.219 --> 07:10.222
[elevator dings]
[residents chattering]

07:11.598 --> 07:13.934
CHARLES:
Wow. Good turnout.

07:13.934 --> 07:15.394
I don't know any of these people.

07:16.436 --> 07:19.273
‐ Oh my god, there's food! Fantastic!

07:19.273 --> 07:20.649
‐ No sneeze guard, no thank you.

07:20.649 --> 07:22.776
Might as well lick the fingers
of every person in the building.

07:22.776 --> 07:25.153
‐ Teddy Dimas lives on six.

07:25.153 --> 07:26.822
Owns Dimas' Delis.

07:26.822 --> 07:28.407
Great guy, great dips.

07:28.407 --> 07:30.659
Deaf son. Mm!
[crunch]

07:30.659 --> 07:31.994
Oh my god. Oh my god.

07:31.994 --> 07:34.371
Mm! You know, this is all I eat.

07:34.746 --> 07:37.040
Dips for dinner. I bet I have not had

07:37.040 --> 07:39.334
a regular entrée for years.

07:39.334 --> 07:41.920
Granted, I've lost 14 pounds
and a significant amount of hair,

07:41.920 --> 07:43.046
but it's totally worth it.

07:43.046 --> 07:44.965
‐ I'm gonna go sit down.

07:45.841 --> 07:48.802
‐ Why the fuck is everyone standing?

07:48.802 --> 07:51.180
You see these chairs?
What do you think they might be for?

07:51.180 --> 07:53.265
[guests murmuring]
Come on! Come on!

07:53.265 --> 07:55.058
[clapping hands]

07:55.058 --> 07:58.937
This won't take long
unless you make it take long!

07:58.937 --> 08:00.147
[sighs]

08:01.565 --> 08:03.150
Now‐‐
‐ Uh, Bunny, if I may.

08:03.150 --> 08:04.484
‐ Oh Jesus.

08:04.484 --> 08:06.778
‐ I'm Dr. Grover Stanley, and I'm sure

08:06.778 --> 08:08.906
we're all grieving the loss of Tim Kono.

08:08.906 --> 08:10.032
If‐if you need to talk privately

08:10.032 --> 08:12.409
about Tim or whatever,

08:12.409 --> 08:15.329
I live on six, and I take Venmo.
[murmuring]

08:15.329 --> 08:17.831
‐ Ooh. A therapist is
always a fun suspect.

08:17.831 --> 08:20.834
Plus, he's desperate. Always good.
BUNNY: Due to

08:20.834 --> 08:23.378
the shocking nature of this incident,

08:23.378 --> 08:25.881
I'm told we need to do this...

08:26.798 --> 08:29.718
for some bullshit insurance purposes.

08:30.177 --> 08:31.678
The family's in Japan,

08:31.678 --> 08:33.680
where the body is already being flown,

08:33.680 --> 08:36.642
so... um, does anybody have anything

08:36.642 --> 08:38.393
they would like to share

08:38.393 --> 08:40.145
about Tim Kono?

08:40.145 --> 08:41.980
‐ Here we go.

08:41.980 --> 08:44.483
Time for the killer to make himself known.

08:45.192 --> 08:46.860
[whispers]
That was from my show.

08:46.860 --> 08:48.654
[recording app beeps]

08:48.654 --> 08:51.240
BUNNY:
A lovely memory?

08:51.865 --> 08:53.283
A kindness?
[yawns]

08:55.410 --> 08:57.287
Anyone?

08:57.913 --> 08:59.039
Yes.
‐ Does this mean

08:59.039 --> 09:00.791
we get to use our fireplaces again?

09:00.791 --> 09:03.252
‐ Yeah, he was the guy
with bad asthma, right?

09:03.252 --> 09:05.754
Since he's dead, we should
be able to use them now.

09:05.754 --> 09:08.549
‐ We can talk fireplaces
at our next board meeting.

09:08.549 --> 09:11.385
‐ Wait, Tim was the reason
we couldn't use our fireplaces?

09:11.385 --> 09:14.096
I hated that guy.
NEIGHBOR: He ruined Christmas!

09:14.096 --> 09:15.973
‐ He once yelled at me.
He once yelled at me

09:15.973 --> 09:17.891
for smoking outside!
BUNNY: Look,

09:17.891 --> 09:20.853
nobody liked him, but can
we all just be grateful he's gone?

09:20.853 --> 09:23.564
Say something nice and move on! Shit.

09:23.564 --> 09:25.649
‐ Uh, excuse me.
[chair scraping]

09:25.649 --> 09:28.235
That apartment is mine, hm?

09:28.235 --> 09:30.529
I lived next to that miserable man

09:30.529 --> 09:33.031
for eight years,
and I need those extra rooms.

09:33.031 --> 09:36.535
‐ Well, yes, Ms. Idoko.
We have you down on the waiting list‐‐

09:36.535 --> 09:39.329
‐ Ah! Ah! Ah! Ah! Ah! Ah!
There is no waiting list.

09:39.329 --> 09:41.331
The apartment is mine.

09:41.331 --> 09:44.376
‐ Wouldn't be the first New Yorker
to kill for good real estate.

09:44.376 --> 09:46.545
[soft laugh]
[man crying]

09:49.715 --> 09:52.050
[continues crying]

09:52.050 --> 09:54.052
Excuse me?

09:54.052 --> 09:55.721
Were you close with Tim?

09:55.721 --> 09:57.514
‐ And do you consent to being recorded?

09:57.514 --> 09:58.891
Just say anything to agree.

09:58.891 --> 10:01.226
‐ No, please.
‐ Thanks, perfect.

10:01.935 --> 10:03.353
Last night...

10:04.062 --> 10:06.690
Sorry.
Last night my cat, Evelyn, died.

10:06.690 --> 10:08.609
I'm sorry, I can't‐‐
I don't like doing this.

10:09.526 --> 10:11.695
‐ Time, please.
Thank you. We're gonna cut.

10:11.695 --> 10:13.947
Um, I like the emotion.

10:13.947 --> 10:17.618
Keep that, but I kinda need
you to enunciate better.

10:17.618 --> 10:20.287
Do you have anything?
‐ The crying is covering the dialogue.

10:20.287 --> 10:23.457
‐ Oh, that's a good‐‐ that's a good note.
Okay. So, try it again,

10:23.457 --> 10:25.584
and it's kind of, in a weird way,

10:25.584 --> 10:27.753
an upbeat story.
So just, when you're ready,

10:27.753 --> 10:29.796
and... action.

10:30.214 --> 10:31.882
‐ My cat,

10:31.882 --> 10:33.884
my beautiful Evelyn...

10:34.885 --> 10:36.220
she died last night.

10:37.513 --> 10:39.014
‐ Your cat?
‐ Mm‐hmm.

10:39.014 --> 10:40.474
NEIGHBOR:
Howard?

10:40.474 --> 10:41.934
Did you say Evelyn died?

10:41.934 --> 10:43.936
‐ Yes. Last night.
[neighbor gasps]

10:43.936 --> 10:45.771
‐ Oh...
[Howard crying]

10:45.771 --> 10:47.147
‐ What's wrong, Howard?

10:47.147 --> 10:49.191
[murmuring]
‐ Evelyn died. The sweet blond tabby

10:49.191 --> 10:52.069
who used to come visiting
through all the window boxes.

10:52.069 --> 10:55.781
Evelyn? Oh no!
She died?

10:55.781 --> 10:58.283
‐ Yes! Evelyn is dead!

10:58.283 --> 11:00.285
[residents murmuring]

11:00.285 --> 11:03.330
‐ Yeah, I'm sure we're all grieving
the death of our dear Evelyn,

11:03.330 --> 11:04.831
and just a quick reminder.

11:04.831 --> 11:06.959
I live on six and Venmo.

11:08.001 --> 11:10.546
‐ Maybe we should make
a podcast about Evelyn.

11:10.546 --> 11:11.672
[Oliver groans]

11:12.673 --> 11:15.676
♪

11:16.510 --> 11:18.095
‐ [singing] Dips for dinner.

11:18.095 --> 11:20.180
♪ Dips for dinner, I'm a nut for dips... ♪

11:20.180 --> 11:22.891
‐ So, our victim is
less likable than a dead cat.

11:22.891 --> 11:25.269
‐ Hey, you know what?
I think we should talk to Ursula.

11:25.269 --> 11:27.771
‐ The sea witch?
‐ No, no, no. The building manager.

11:27.771 --> 11:30.440
If anyone has information
on Tim, she does.

11:30.440 --> 11:31.942
‐ Oliver?

11:31.942 --> 11:34.528
Can I speak with you?
‐ Of course, Bun Bun.

11:36.071 --> 11:39.408
First of all, let me say,
you look fantastic.

11:39.408 --> 11:41.285
You gotta give me the name of your guy.

11:41.285 --> 11:43.078
You look like a damn kid.

11:43.078 --> 11:46.081
‐ Mm. Your building fees
are eight months past due.

11:46.081 --> 11:48.458
This is your final notice
before the board will be forced

11:48.458 --> 11:51.587
to take drastic actions.
‐ I‐‐ B‐Bunny, w‐we're friends,

11:51.587 --> 11:54.256
and‐‐
‐ That's why I'm using a friendly tone.

11:54.256 --> 11:56.258
Don't fuck with me, OIiver.

11:56.258 --> 11:59.011
‐ Mm, I can't think of
anything less pleasant.

11:59.011 --> 12:01.638
‐ That makes two of us.

12:01.638 --> 12:04.933
[Howard sobbing]

12:05.934 --> 12:08.478
‐ I didn't cry that much
when my mother died.

12:10.480 --> 12:12.983
‐ Is that true, or are you lying?

12:12.983 --> 12:14.818
‐ Why would I lie
about something like that?

12:17.821 --> 12:20.741
I don't know what I'm supposed
to do right now...

12:21.867 --> 12:25.704
‐ I'm totally migraining.
You guys meet the sea witch without me.

12:30.375 --> 12:33.128
‐ What did you say to her?
‐ Just making conversation.

12:33.545 --> 12:34.963
‐ Mm. Not your thing.

12:36.256 --> 12:38.258
Grab those, won't you? [sighs]

12:40.677 --> 12:41.970
And that tray, too.

12:42.596 --> 12:45.599
♪ light piano playing ♪

13:10.666 --> 13:13.043
[clicking, beep]

13:16.380 --> 13:18.382
Hi.

13:18.382 --> 13:21.093
I'm not sure why I'm doing this.

13:21.969 --> 13:24.555
Maybe it's because nobody
gave a shit about Tim,

13:24.555 --> 13:27.474
and I want something on record in case...

13:35.190 --> 13:37.067
Who is Tim Kono?

13:37.067 --> 13:38.277
♪

13:38.277 --> 13:39.820
Who was?

13:47.995 --> 13:50.998
♪ low strings playing ♪

13:51.665 --> 13:55.377
I met him here, at the Arconia,
when we were 10.

13:56.753 --> 14:00.215
I interrupted a game
he had to play every day.

14:00.215 --> 14:01.800
‐ I don't know you.

14:01.800 --> 14:03.802
I know everyone who
lives in this building.

14:04.845 --> 14:07.347
‐ I don't live in this building.
My aunt does.

14:07.347 --> 14:08.891
Salma Ramirez.

14:10.100 --> 14:13.353
‐ 12A. I like her.

14:13.353 --> 14:15.898
She gives out whole
candy bars on Halloween.

14:15.898 --> 14:19.067
‐ I live on Long Island where they
give out loose cigarettes and lighters.

14:19.985 --> 14:22.237
‐ Yeah. You look pretty poor.

14:22.237 --> 14:25.324
MABEL: It's true Tim didn't
get along with a lot of people.

14:27.868 --> 14:30.704
‐ What are you drawing?
‐ The beach near my house.

14:31.538 --> 14:33.790
MABEL:
He was direct, but he never lied.

14:34.875 --> 14:36.585
‐ It's not very good.

14:36.585 --> 14:38.420
MABEL:
Maybe that's why I liked him.

14:39.129 --> 14:40.130
‐ You reading that?

14:40.130 --> 14:42.174
‐ No. I'm too poor to read.

14:44.259 --> 14:47.721
It's about two brothers
who solve crimes in Bayport,

14:47.721 --> 14:50.015
where I live. It's a whole series.

14:51.058 --> 14:53.352
